'''World Suicide Prevention Day''' ('''WSPD''') is an awareness day observed on 10 September every year, in order to provide worldwide commitment and action to prevent suicides, with various activities around the world.<ref name=sitnews>{{cite news|title=Alaska Observes World Suicide Prevention Day and Alaska Suicide Prevention Month |url=http://www.sitnews.us/0904news/091104/091104_suicide_prevention.html|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=SitNews|date=11 September 2004}}</ref>  The [[International Association for Suicide Prevention]] (IASP), collaborates with the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the [[World Federation for Mental Health]], to host World Suicide Prevention Day.<ref name=suicidology>{{cite web|title=Suicide in the U.S.A. Based on Current (2007) Statistics |url=http://www.suicidology.org/c/document_library/get_file?folderId=236&name=DLFE-368.pdf|publisher=American Association of Suicidology|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> In 2011 an estimated 40 countries held awareness events to mark the occasion.<ref name=lfp/> The United Nations issued 'National Policy for Suicide Prevention' in the 1990s which some countries use as a basis for their suicide policies.<ref name="united nations"/>

{{quote|text=Suicide has a number of complex and interrelated and underlying contributing factors ... that can contribute to the feelings of pain and hopelessness. Having access to means to kill oneself – most typically firearms, medicines and poisons – is also a risk factor.<ref name=sitnews/>|source=Campaign release}}

==Background==
{{As of |2011}}, an estimated one million people per year die by suicide or "a death every 40 seconds or about 3,000 every day."<ref name=lfp>{{cite news|last=QMI Agency|title=Inuit youth celebrate life on World Suicide Day |url=http://www.lfpress.com/news/canada/2011/09/10/18666426.html|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=London Free Press|date=10 September 2011}}</ref> According to WHO there are twenty people who have a [[failed suicide attempt]] for every one that is successful, at a rate approximately one every three seconds.<ref name=time>{{cite news|last=Melnick|first=Meredith|title=It’s World Suicide Prevention Day: What You Can Do to Help|url=http://healthland.time.com/2010/09/10/its-world-suicide-prevention%C2%A0day-what-you-can-do-to-help/|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Time|date=10 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=dailymail>{{cite news|title=Suicide every 40 seconds|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-361601/Suicide-40-seconds.html|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=7 September 2005}}</ref> Suicide is the "most common cause of death for people aged 15 – 24."<ref name=Beausejour/> More people die from suicide than from murder and war; it is the 13th leading cause of death worldwide.<ref name=sitnews/><ref name=rtenews/> According to WHO, suicide accounts for nearly half of all violent deaths in the world.<ref name=dailymail/> [[Brian Mishara]], IASP president, noted that, "more people kill themselves than die in all wars, terrorist acts and interpersonal violence combined."<ref name=scoop/> The number of people who die by suicide is expected to reach 1.5 million per year by 2020.<ref name=rtenews>{{cite news|title=World Suicide Prevention Day is marked |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/0910/suicide.html|accessdate=11 June 2012 |newspaper=Raidió Teilifís Éireann|date=10 September 2004}}</ref> 

The UN noted that [[suicide bombers]]' deaths are seen as secondary to their goal of killing other people or specific targets and the bombers are not otherwise typical of people committing suicide.<ref name="united nations"/>

==Pesticides==
According to a WHO press release, one third of worldwide suicides were committed with [[pesticide]]s, "some of which were forbidden by United Nations (UN) conventions."<ref name="united nations">{{cite web|title=Press Conference by World Health Organization on Suicide Prevention |url=http://www.un.org/News/briefings/docs/2006/060908_Suicide.doc.htm|publisher=United Nations Department of Public Information|accessdate=11 June 2012|format=Press Conference|date=8 September 2006}}</ref> WHO urges Asian countries to restrict pesticides that are commonly used in failed attempts, especially [[organophosphate]]-based pesticides that are banned by international conventions but still made in and exported by some Asian countries.<ref name=CBCNews>{{cite news|title=Restrict pesticides to reduce suicides: WHO |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/story/2006/11/09/pesticide-suicides.html|accessdate=12 June 2012|newspaper=CBC News|date=9 November 2006}}</ref> From 1996–2006 pesticide ingestion accounted for an estimated 60–90 percent of suicides in China, [[Malaysia]], Sri Lanka, and [[Trinidad]].<ref name=CBCNews/> 
WHO reports an increase in pesticide suicides in other Asian countries as well as [[Central America|Central]] and South America.<ref name=CBCNews/> It is estimated that such painful failed attempts could be reduced by legalizing controlled voluntary euthanasia options, as implemented in [[Switzerland]].

==Country information==<!--- Any better section title?--->
Of the 34 member countries of the [[Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development]], a group of [[developed countries]] that uses [[market economy]] to improve the [[Human Development Index]], South Korea had the highest [[suicide rate]].<ref name=LATimes/> In 2011 South Korea's Ministry of Health and Welfare enacted legislation coinciding with WSPD to address the high rate.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news|last=Choi|first=Jung-yoon|title=South Korea to step up suicide prevention efforts: In 2009, 15,413 people took their lives, a rate that is three times higher than two decades ago. Officials plan to boost suicide prevention funding and install surveillance devices at key sites.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/sep/08/world/la-fg-south-korea-suicide-20110909|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=8 September 2011}}</ref>  

In some countries, such as China, young people 15–34 years old are more likely to die by suicide than by any other means.<ref name=BBCNewsBeijing>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=James|title=Chinese youth 'face suicide risk'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7608575.stm|accessdate=12 June 2012|newspaper=BBC News, Beijing|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> 

According to WHO, in 2009 the four countries with the highest rates of suicide were all in Eastern Europe; [[Slovenia]] had the fourth highest rate preceded by [[Russia]], Latvia, and [[Belarus]].<ref>{{cite news|title=News Roundup: Ljubljana|url=http://www.sta.si/en/vest.php?s=a&id=1425769|accessdate=12 June 2012|newspaper=Slovenska Tiskovna Agencija|date=9 October 2009}}</ref> This stays within findings from the start of the WSPD event in 2003 when the highest rates were also found in Eastern European countries.<ref name=IASPpr>{{cite web|title=Celebrating the 1st World Suicide Prevention Day 10 September 2003|url=http://iasp.info/wspd/2003_wspd.php|work=Press Release|publisher=International Association for Suicide Prevention|accessdate=12 June 2012}} adapted from the chapter on "Self-Directed Violence" from the ''World Report on Violence and Health'', [[World Health Organization]], Geneva, 2002.</ref> The countries with the lowest rates tend to be in Latin America, "[[Muslim countries]] and a few Asian countries."<ref name=IASPpr/> There is a lack of information from most African countries.<ref name=IASPpr/>

